        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "End of Course Performance",
          "Pass vs Fail vs Withdrawal",
          "3983 OU students",
          "1 OULAD Course",
          "Student Characteristics, \nLMS logs",
          "[forumng, homepage, oucollaborate, oucontent, page, quiz, resource, subpage, url, gender, region, highest_education, age_band, num_of_prev_attempts, studied_credits, disability]",
          "Weeks 5/10/15 and 20  ",
          "Data is converted into a tabular dataset. Authors report to do feature selection, data cleaning and transformation… these steps are not specified...\n\nOn the graph network, each student is a node and the graph is created based on similarity:\n\n- Pearson Correlation, \n- Cosine Similarity, \nTanimoto Coefficient.",
          "Linear Regression,\nSVM, \nMLP, Graph Convolutional Network (GCN), GCN-Cosine, MTGNN\n",
          "Holdout Method",
          "General - Pass vs Fail\n{Accuracy: 0.8498 - MTGNN, F1-Score: 0.7365 - MTGNN, Recall: 0.6846 - MTGNN}\n\nWeek 10 - Pass vs Fail\n{Accuracy: 0.7622 - MTGNN}\n",
          "Authors propose a Graph Neural Network approach tto predict student performance.\n\nAuthors perform multiple experiments:\n\n1. Show if model is better than other approaches,\n\n2. Show results for early prediction.\n\n3. Results for Multiple Topologies vs Single Topological models.\n\nThere is a comparison of results using 1 vs 1 computation of metrics. Results of Pass vs Fail are considerably “worse” than Pass vs Withdraw.\n\nThis difference is less noticeable for early prediction → best tradeoff seems to be Week 10.",
          "- Analysis is performed using data from a single course.\n\n- Aggregate metrics are not revealed.\n\n- Uses Holdout Method"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 8
    }
